# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fennel-lisp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] An **abstract syntax tree** (**AST**) is a data structure used in computer science to represent the structure of a program or code snippet.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] It is a tree representation of the abstract syntactic structure of text (often source code) written in a formal language.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Each node of the tree denotes a construct occurring in the text.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] It is sometimes called just a **syntax tree**.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] The syntax is "abstract" in the sense that it does not represent every detail appearing in the real syntax, but rather just the structural or content-related details.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] For instance, grouping parentheses are implicit in the tree structure, so these do not have to be represented as separate nodes.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Likewise, a syntactic construct like an if-condition-then statement may be denoted by means of a single node with three branches.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] This distinguishes abstract syntax trees from concrete syntax trees, traditionally designated parse trees.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Parse trees are typically built by a parser during the source code translation and compiling process.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Once built, additional information is added to the AST by means of subsequent processing, e.g., contextual analysis.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Abstract syntax trees are also used in program analysis and program transformation systems.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Abstract syntax trees are data structures widely used in compilers to represent the structure of program code.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] An AST is usually the result of the syntax analysis phase of a compiler.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] It often serves as an intermediate representation of the program through several stages that the compiler requires, and has a strong effect on the final output of the compiler.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Languages are often ambiguous by nature.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] In order to avoid this ambiguity, programming languages are often specified as a context-free grammar (CFG).
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] However, there are often aspects of programming languages that a CFG can't express, but are part of the language and are documented in its specification.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] These are details that require a context to determine their validity and behavior.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] For example, if a language allows new types to be declared, a CFG cannot predict the names of such types nor the way in which they should be used.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Even if a language has a predefined set of types, enforcing proper usage usually requires some context.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Another example is duck typing, where the type of an element can change depending on context.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Operator overloading is yet another case where correct usage and final function are context-dependent.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] The design of an AST is often closely linked with the design of a compiler and its expected features.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] These requirements can be used to design the data structure for the AST.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Some operations will always require two elements, such as the two terms for addition.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] However, some language constructs require an arbitrarily large number of children, such as argument lists passed to programs from the command shell.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] As a result, an AST used to represent code written in such a language has to also be flexible enough to allow for the quick addition of an unknown quantity of children.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] To support compiler verification it should be possible to unparse an AST into source code form.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] The source code produced should be sufficiently similar to the original in appearance and identical in execution, upon recompilation.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] The AST is used intensively during semantic analysis, where the compiler checks for correct usage of the elements of the program and the language.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] The compiler also generates symbol tables based on the AST during semantic analysis.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] A complete traversal of the tree allows verification of the correctness of the program.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] After verifying correctness, the AST serves as the base for code generation.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] The AST is often used to generate an intermediate representation (IR), sometimes called an intermediate language, for the code generation.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] AST differencing, or for short tree differencing, consists of computing the list of differences between two ASTs.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] This list of differences is typically called an edit script.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] The edit script directly refers to the AST of the code.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] For instance, an edit action may result in the addition of a new AST node representing a function.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] An AST is a powerful abstraction to perform code clone detection.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Let ${\mathcal {O}}=\{{\mathcal {O_{\alpha }}}\}_{\alpha \in \mathrm {Arity} (S)}$ be an $\mathrm {Arity} (S)$ -indexed family of disjoint sets of *operators*.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] If o is an operator arity $(s_{1},\dots ,s_{n})s$ we say that o has sort s and has n arguments of sorts $s_{1},\dots ,s_{n}$ .
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Fix S be a finite set of sorts, and ${\mathcal {O}}$ an $\mathrm {Arity} (S)$ -indexed family of disjoint sets of *operators*.
[src:fennel-lisp/abstract-syntax-tree] Let ${\mathcal {X}}=\{{\mathcal {X}}_{s}\}_{s\in S}$ be an S -indexed family of disjoint sets of variables.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] In computer programming, **homoiconicity** (from the Greek words *homo-* meaning "the same" and *icon* meaning "representation") is an informal property of some programming languages.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] A language is **homoiconic** if a program written in it can be manipulated as data using the language.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] The program's internal representation can thus be inferred just by reading the program itself.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] This property is often summarized by saying that the language treats code as data.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] The informality of the property arises from the fact that, strictly, this applies to almost all programming languages.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] No consensus exists on a precise definition of the property.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] In a homoiconic language, the primary representation of programs is also a data structure in a primitive type of the language itself.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] This makes metaprogramming easier than in a language without this property: reflection in the language (examining the program's entities at runtime) depends on a single, homogeneous structure, and it does not have to handle several different structures that would appear in a complex syntax.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] Homoiconic languages typically include full support of syntactic macros, allowing the programmer to express transformations of programs in a concise way.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] A commonly cited example is Lisp, which was created to allow for easy list manipulations and where the structure is given by S-expressions that take the form of nested lists, and can be manipulated by other Lisp code.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] Other examples are the programming languages Clojure (a contemporary dialect of Lisp), Rebol (also its successor Red), Refal, Prolog, XSLT, and possibly Julia (see the section “Implementation methods” for more details).
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] The researchers implicated in this quote might be neurophysiologist and cybernetician Warren Sturgis McCulloch (note the difference in the surname from the note) and philosopher, logician and mathematician Charles Sanders Peirce.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] Pierce indeed used the term "icon" in his Semiotic Theory.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] According to Peirce, there are three kinds of sign in communication: the icon, the index and the symbol.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] The icon is the simplest representation: an icon physically resembles that which it denotes.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] One advantage of homoiconicity is that extending the language with new concepts typically becomes simpler, as data representing code can be passed between the meta and base layer of the program.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] The abstract syntax tree of a function may be composed and manipulated as a data structure in the meta layer, and then evaluated.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] It can be much easier to understand how to manipulate the code since it can be more easily understood as simple data (since the format of the language itself is as a data format).
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] A typical demonstration of homoiconicity is the meta-circular evaluator.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] All Von Neumann architecture systems, which includes the vast majority of general purpose computers today, can implicitly be described as homoiconic due to the way that raw machine code executes in memory, the data type being bytes in memory.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] However, this feature can also be abstracted to the programming language level.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] Languages such as Lisp and its dialects, such as Scheme, Clojure, and Racket employ S-expressions to achieve homoiconicity, and are considered the "Purest" forms of homoiconicity, as these languages use the same representation for both data and code.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] Other languages provide data structures for easily and efficiently manipulating code.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] Notable examples of this weaker form of homoiconicity include Julia, Nim, and Elixir.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] Lisp uses S-expressions as an external representation for data and code.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] S-expressions can be read with the primitive Lisp function `READ`.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] `READ` returns Lisp data: lists, symbols, numbers, strings.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] The primitive Lisp function `EVAL` uses Lisp code represented as Lisp data, computes side-effects and returns a result.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] The result will be printed by the primitive function `PRINT`, which creates an external S-expression from Lisp data.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] Lisp data, a list using different data types: (sub)lists, symbols, strings and integer numbers.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] The example uses lists, symbols and numbers.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] The operator `:-` separates the head and the body of a clause.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] With `assert/1`* we add it to the existing clauses (add it to the "database"), so we can call it later.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] In other languages we would call it "creating a function during runtime".
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] We can also remove clauses from the database with `abolish/1`, or `retract/1`.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] `call` is analogous to Lisp's `eval` function.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] The concept of treating code as data and the manipulation and evaluation thereof can be demonstrated very neatly in Rebol.
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] (Rebol, unlike Lisp, does not require parentheses to separate expressions).
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] (`repeat` is in fact a built-in function in Rebol and is not a language construct or keyword).
[src:fennel-lisp/homoiconicity] The block can still be interpreted by using the `do` function provided in Rebol (similar to `eval` in Lisp).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was originally created as a practical mathematical notation for computer programs, influenced by (though not originally derived from) the notation of Alonzo Church's lambda calculus.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It quickly became a favored programming language for artificial intelligence (AI) research.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As one of the earliest programming languages, Lisp pioneered many ideas in computer science, including tree data structures, automatic storage management, dynamic typing, conditionals, higher-order functions, recursion, the self-hosting compiler, and the read–eval–print loop.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The name *LISP* derives from "List Processor".
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Linked lists are one of Lisp's major data structures, and Lisp source code is made of lists.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp programs can manipulate source code as a data structure, giving rise to the macro systems that allow programmers to create new syntax or new domain-specific languages embedded in Lisp.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The interchangeability of code and data gives Lisp its instantly recognizable syntax.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] All program code is written as *s-expressions*, or parenthesized lists.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A function call or syntactic form is written as a list with the function or operator's name first, and the arguments following; for instance, a function `f` that takes three arguments would be called as `(f arg1 arg2 arg3)`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] John McCarthy began developing Lisp in 1958 while he was at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Due to these factors, he consulted on the design of the Fortran List Processing Language, which was implemented as a Fortran library.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, he was dissatisfied with it because it did not support recursion or a modern if-then-else statement (which was a new concept when Lisp was first introduced).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's original notation used bracketed "M-expressions" that would be translated into S-expressions.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As an example, the M-expression `car[cons[A,B]]` is equivalent to the S-expression `(car (cons A B))`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Once Lisp was implemented, programmers rapidly chose to use S-expressions, and M-expressions were abandoned.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions surfaced again with short-lived attempts of MLisp by Horace Enea and CGOL by Vaughan Pratt.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was first implemented by Steve Russell on an IBM 704 computer using punched cards.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Russell was working for McCarthy at the time and realized (to McCarthy's surprise) that the Lisp *eval* function could be implemented in machine code.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The result was a working Lisp interpreter which could be used to run Lisp programs, or more properly, "evaluate Lisp expressions".
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp dialects still use `car` and `cdr` (/kɑːr/ and /ˈkʊdər/) for the operations that return the first item in a list and the rest of the list, respectively.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy published Lisp's design in a paper in *Communications of the ACM* on April 1, 1960, entitled "Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine, Part I".
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] He showed that with a few simple operators and a notation for anonymous functions borrowed from Church, one can build a Turing-complete language for algorithms.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This compiler introduced the Lisp model of incremental compilation, in which compiled and interpreted functions can intermix freely.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The language used in Hart and Levin's memo is much closer to modern Lisp style than McCarthy's earlier code.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Garbage collection routines were developed by MIT graduate student Daniel Edwards, prior to 1962.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] During the 1980s and 1990s, a great effort was made to unify the work on new Lisp dialects (mostly successors to Maclisp such as ZetaLisp and NIL (New Implementation of Lisp)) into a single language.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The new language, Common Lisp, was somewhat compatible with the dialects it replaced (the book *Common Lisp the Language* notes the compatibility of various constructs).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In 1994, ANSI published the Common Lisp standard, "ANSI X3.226-1994 Information Technology Programming Language Common Lisp".
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Since its inception, Lisp was closely connected with the artificial intelligence research community, especially on PDP-10 systems.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was used as the implementation of the language Micro Planner, which was used in the famous AI system SHRDLU.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In the 1970s, as AI research spawned commercial offshoots, the performance of existing Lisp systems became a growing issue, as programmers needed to be familiar with the performance ramifications of the various techniques and choices involved in the implementation of Lisp.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Over its sixty-year history, Lisp has spawned many variations on the core theme of an S-expression language.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Some of these variations have been standardized and implemented by different groups with different priorities (for example, both Common Lisp and Scheme have multiple implementations).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, in other cases a software project defines a Lisp without a standard and there is no clear distinction between the dialect and the implementation (for example, Clojure and Emacs Lisp fall into this category).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Differences between dialects (and/or implementations) may be quite visible—for instance, Common Lisp uses the keyword `defun` to name a function, but Scheme uses `define`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Within a dialect that is standardized conforming implementations support the same core language, but with different extensions and libraries.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This sometimes also creates quite visible changes from the base language - for instance, Guile (an implementation of Scheme) uses `define*` to create functions which can have default arguments and/or keyword arguments, neither of which are standardized.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] After having declined somewhat in the 1990s, Lisp has experienced a resurgence of interest after 2000.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Most new activity has been focused around implementations of Common Lisp, Scheme, Emacs Lisp, Clojure, and Racket, and includes development of new portable libraries and applications.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Many new Lisp programmers were inspired by writers such as Paul Graham and Eric S.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Raymond to pursue a language others considered antiquated.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] New Lisp programmers often describe the language as an eye-opening experience and claim to be substantially more productive than in other languages.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This increase in awareness may be contrasted to the "AI winter" and Lisp's brief gain in the mid-1990s.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As of 2010, there were eleven actively maintained Common Lisp implementations.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] *Common-lisp.net* is a hosting site for open source Common Lisp projects.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Quicklisp is a library manager for Common Lisp.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Fifty years of Lisp (1958–2008) was celebrated at LISP50@OOPSLA.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] There are regular local user meetings in Boston, Vancouver, and Hamburg.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Other events include the European Common Lisp Meeting, the European Lisp Symposium and an International Lisp Conference.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme community actively maintains over twenty implementations.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Several significant new implementations (Chicken, Gambit, Gauche, Ikarus, Larceny, Ypsilon) have been developed in the 2000s (decade).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Revised5 Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme standard of Scheme was widely accepted in the Scheme community.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme Requests for Implementation process has created a lot of quasi-standard libraries and extensions for Scheme.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] User communities of individual Scheme implementations continue to grow.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A new language standardization process was started in 2003 and led to the R6RS Scheme standard in 2007.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Academic use of Scheme for teaching computer science seems to have declined somewhat.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Some universities are no longer using Scheme in their computer science introductory courses; MIT now uses Python instead of Scheme for its undergraduate computer science program and MITx massive open online course.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] There are several new dialects of Lisp: Arc, Hy, Nu, Liskell, and LFE (Lisp Flavored Erlang).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The parser for Julia is implemented in Femtolisp, a dialect of Scheme (Julia is inspired by Scheme, which in turn is a Lisp dialect).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp and Scheme represent two major streams of Lisp development.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] These languages embody significantly different design choices.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The primary influences were Lisp Machine Lisp, Maclisp, NIL, S-1 Lisp, Spice Lisp, and Scheme.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It has many of the features of Lisp Machine Lisp (a large Lisp dialect used to program Lisp Machines), but was designed to be efficiently implementable on any personal computer or workstation.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp is a general-purpose programming language and thus has a large language standard including many built-in data types, functions, macros and other language elements, and an object system (Common Lisp Object System).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp also borrowed certain features from Scheme such as lexical scoping and lexical closures.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp implementations are available for targeting different platforms such as the LLVM, the Java virtual machine, x86-64, PowerPC, Alpha, ARM, Motorola 68000, and MIPS, and operating systems such as Windows, macOS, Linux, Solaris, FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD, Dragonfly BSD, and Heroku.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Scheme is a statically scoped and properly tail-recursive dialect of the Lisp programming language invented by Guy L.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It was designed to have exceptionally clear and simple semantics and few different ways to form expressions.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Designed about a decade earlier than Common Lisp, Scheme is a more minimalist design.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It has a much smaller set of standard features but with certain implementation features (such as tail-call optimization and full continuations) not specified in Common Lisp.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A wide variety of programming paradigms, including imperative, functional, and message passing styles, find convenient expression in Scheme.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Scheme continues to evolve with a series of standards (Revisedn Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme) and a series of Scheme Requests for Implementation.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is a dialect of Lisp that targets mainly the Java virtual machine, and the Common Language Runtime (CLR), the Python VM, the Ruby VM YARV, and compiling to JavaScript.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It is designed to be a pragmatic general-purpose language.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure draws considerable influences from Haskell and places a very strong emphasis on immutability.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure provides access to Java frameworks and libraries, with optional type hints and type inference, so that calls to Java can avoid reflection and enable fast primitive operations.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is not designed to be backwards compatible with other Lisp dialects.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Further, Lisp dialects are used as scripting languages in many applications, with the best-known being Emacs Lisp in the Emacs editor, AutoLISP and later Visual Lisp in AutoCAD, Nyquist in Audacity, and Scheme in LilyPond.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The potential small size of a useful Scheme interpreter makes it particularly popular for embedded scripting.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Examples include SIOD and TinyScheme, both of which have been successfully embedded in the GIMP image processor under the generic name "Script-fu".
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] LIBREP, a Lisp interpreter by John Harper originally based on the Emacs Lisp language, has been embedded in the Sawfish window manager.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has officially standardized dialects: R6RS Scheme, R7RS Scheme, IEEE Scheme, ANSI Common Lisp and ISO ISLISP.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was the first language where the structure of program code is represented faithfully and directly in a standard data structure—a quality much later dubbed "homoiconicity".
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp functions can be manipulated, altered or even created within a Lisp program without lower-level manipulations.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is generally considered one of the main advantages of the language with regard to its expressive power, and makes the language suitable for syntactic macros and meta-circular evaluation.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A conditional using an *if–then–else* syntax was invented by McCarthy for a chess program written in Fortran.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] He proposed its inclusion in ALGOL, but it was not made part of the Algol 58 specification.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For Lisp, McCarthy used the more general *cond*-structure.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Algol 60 took up *if–then–else* and popularized it.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp deeply influenced Alan Kay, the leader of the research team that developed Smalltalk at Xerox PARC; and in turn Lisp was influenced by Smalltalk, with later dialects adopting object-oriented programming features (inheritance classes, encapsulating instances, message passing, etc.) in the 1970s.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Flavors object system introduced the concept of multiple inheritance and the mixin.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Common Lisp Object System provides multiple inheritance, multimethods with multiple dispatch, and first-class generic functions, yielding a flexible and powerful form of dynamic dispatch.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Many years later, Alan Kay suggested that as a result of the confluence of these features, only Smalltalk and Lisp could be regarded as properly conceived object-oriented programming systems.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp introduced the concept of automatic garbage collection, in which the system walks the heap looking for unused memory.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Progress in modern sophisticated garbage collection algorithms such as generational garbage collection was stimulated by its use in Lisp.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Largely because of its resource requirements with respect to early computing hardware (including early microprocessors), Lisp did not become as popular outside of the AI community as Fortran and the ALGOL-descended C language.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because of its suitability to complex and dynamic applications, Lisp enjoyed some resurgence of popular interest in the 2010s.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp is an expression oriented language.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Unlike most other languages, no distinction is made between "expressions" and "statements"; all code and data are written as expressions.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] When an expression is *evaluated*, it produces a value (possibly multiple values), which can then be embedded into other expressions.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's 1958 paper introduced two types of syntax: *Symbolic expressions* (S-expressions, sexps), which mirror the internal representation of code and data; and *Meta expressions* (M-expressions), which express functions of S-expressions.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions never found favor, and almost all Lisps today use S-expressions to manipulate both code and data.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The use of parentheses is Lisp's most immediately obvious difference from other programming language families.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As a result, students have long given Lisp nicknames such as *Lost In Stupid Parentheses*, or *Lots of Irritating Superfluous Parentheses*.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, the S-expression syntax is also responsible for much of Lisp's power: the syntax is simple and consistent, which facilitates manipulation by computer.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, the syntax of Lisp is not limited to traditional parentheses notation.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It can be extended to include alternative notations.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, XMLisp is a Common Lisp extension that employs the metaobject protocol to integrate S-expressions with the Extensible Markup Language (XML).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The reliance on expressions gives the language great flexibility.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because Lisp functions are written as lists, they can be processed exactly like data.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This allows easy writing of programs which manipulate other programs (metaprogramming).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Many Lisp dialects exploit this feature using macro systems, which enables extension of the language almost without limit.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is written with its elements separated by whitespace, and surrounded by parentheses.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, `(1 2 foo)` is a list whose elements are the three *atoms* `1`, `2`, and `foo`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] These values are implicitly typed: they are respectively two integers and a Lisp-specific data type called a "symbol", and do not have to be declared as such.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The empty list `()` is also represented as the special atom `nil`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is the only entity in Lisp which is both an atom and a list.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Expressions are written as lists, using prefix notation.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The first element in the list is the name of a function, the name of a macro, a lambda expression or the name of a "special operator" (see below).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The remainder of the list are the arguments.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The "quote" before the `foo` in the preceding example is a "special operator" which returns its argument without evaluating it.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Any unquoted expressions are recursively evaluated before the enclosing expression is evaluated.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The third argument is a list; lists can be nested.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators are treated similarly.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The equivalent under infix notation would be "`1 + 2 + 3 + 4`".
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has no notion of operators as implemented in ALGOL-derived languages.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators in Lisp are variadic functions (or *n-ary*), able to take any number of arguments.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] equivalent to `(setq x (+ x 1))`, returning the new value of `x`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] "Special operators" (sometimes called "special forms") provide Lisp's control structure.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, the special operator `if` takes three arguments.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] If the first argument is non-nil, it evaluates to the second argument; otherwise, it evaluates to the third argument.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Of course, this would be more useful if a non-trivial expression had been substituted in place of `nil`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp also provides logical operators **and**, **or** and **not**.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The **and** and **or** operators do short-circuit evaluation and will return their first nil and non-nil argument respectively.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Another special operator, `lambda`, is used to bind variables to values which are then evaluated within an expression.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This operator is also used to create functions: the arguments to `lambda` are a list of arguments, and the expression or expressions to which the function evaluates (the returned value is the value of the last expression that is evaluated).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] evaluates to a function that, when applied, takes one argument, binds it to `arg` and returns the number one greater than that argument.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lambda expressions are treated no differently from named functions; they are invoked the same way.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Here, we're doing a function application: we execute the anonymous function by passing to it the value 5.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Named functions are created by storing a lambda expression in a symbol using the defun macro.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] `(defun f (a) b...)` defines a new function named `f` in the global environment.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] where `setf` is a macro used to set the value of the first argument `fdefinition 'f` to a new function object.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] `fdefinition` is a global function definition for the function named `f`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] `#'` is an abbreviation for `function` special operator, returning a function object.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In the original **LISP** there were two fundamental data types: atoms and lists.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A list was a finite ordered sequence of elements, where each element is either an atom or a list, and an atom was a number or a symbol.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A symbol was essentially a unique named item, written as an alphanumeric string in source code, and used either as a variable name or as a data item in symbolic processing.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, the list `(FOO (BAR 1) 2)` contains three elements: the symbol `FOO`, the list `(BAR 1)`, and the number 2.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The essential difference between atoms and lists was that atoms were immutable and unique.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Two atoms that appeared in different places in source code but were written in exactly the same way represented the same object, whereas each list was a separate object that could be altered independently of other lists and could be distinguished from other lists by comparison operators.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As more data types were introduced in later Lisp dialects, and programming styles evolved, the concept of an atom lost importance.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Many dialects still retained the predicate *atom* for legacy compatibility, defining it true for any object which is not a cons.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is implemented as a singly linked list.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Each cell of this list is called a *cons* (in Scheme, a *pair*) and is composed of two pointers, called the *car* and *cdr*.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] These are respectively equivalent to the `data` and `next` fields discussed in the article *linked list*.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Of the many data structures that can be built out of cons cells, one of the most basic is called a *proper list*.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A proper list is either the special `nil` (empty list) symbol, or a cons in which the `car` points to a datum (which may be another cons structure, such as a list), and the `cdr` points to another proper list.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] If a given cons is taken to be the head of a linked list, then its car points to the first element of the list, and its cdr points to the rest of the list.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the `car` and `cdr` functions are also called `first` and `rest` when referring to conses which are part of a linked list (rather than, say, a tree).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Thus, a Lisp list is not an atomic object, as an instance of a container class in C++ or Java would be.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A list is nothing more than an aggregate of linked conses.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A variable that refers to a given list is simply a pointer to the first cons in the list.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Traversal of a list can be done by *cdring down* the list; that is, taking successive cdrs to visit each cons of the list; or by using any of several higher-order functions to map a function over a list.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because conses and lists are so universal in Lisp systems, it is a common misconception that they are Lisp's only data structures.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In fact, all but the most simplistic Lisps have other data structures, such as vectors (arrays), hash tables, structures, and so forth.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Parenthesized S-expressions represent linked list structures.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] There are several ways to represent the same list as an S-expression.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A cons can be written in *dotted-pair notation* as `(a . b)`, where `a` is the car and `b` the cdr.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A longer proper list might be written `(a .
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is conventionally abbreviated as `(a b c d)` in *list notation*.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] An improper list may be written in a combination of the two – as `(a b c . d)` for the list of three conses whose last cdr is `d` (i.e., the list `(a .
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp provides many built-in procedures for accessing and controlling lists.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lists can be created directly with the `list` procedure, which takes any number of arguments, and returns the list of these arguments.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because of the way that lists are constructed from cons pairs, the `cons` procedure can be used to add an element to the front of a list.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The `cons` procedure is asymmetric in how it handles list arguments, because of how lists are constructed.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The `append` procedure appends two (or more) lists to one another.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp lists, being simple linked lists, can share structure with one another.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] That is to say, two lists can have the same *tail*, or final sequence of conses.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] the lists `foo` and `bar` are `(a b c)` and `(x b c)` respectively.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, the tail `(b c)` is the same structure in both lists.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It is not a copy; the cons cells pointing to `b` and `c` are in the same memory locations for both lists.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Sharing structure rather than copying can give a dramatic performance improvement.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, this technique can interact in undesired ways with functions that alter lists passed to them as arguments.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This changes `foo` to `(a b goose)`, but thereby also changes `bar` to `(x b goose)` – a possibly unexpected result.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This can be a source of bugs, and functions which alter their arguments are documented as *destructive* for this very reason.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Aficionados of functional programming avoid destructive functions.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In the Scheme dialect, which favors the functional style, the names of destructive functions are marked with a cautionary exclamation point, or "bang"—such as `set-car!` (read *set car bang*), which replaces the car of a cons.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In the Common Lisp dialect, destructive functions are commonplace; the equivalent of `set-car!` is named `rplaca` for "replace car".
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This function is rarely seen, however, as Common Lisp includes a special facility, `setf`, to make it easier to define and use destructive functions.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A frequent style in Common Lisp is to write code functionally (without destructive calls) when prototyping, then to add destructive calls as an optimization where it is safe to do so.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp evaluates expressions which are entered by the user.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Symbols and lists evaluate to some other (usually, simpler) expression – for instance, a symbol evaluates to the value of the variable it names; `(+ 2 3)` evaluates to `5`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, most other forms evaluate to themselves: if entering `5` into Lisp, it returns `5`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Any expression can also be marked to prevent it from being evaluated (as is necessary for symbols and lists).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is the role of the `quote` special operator, or its abbreviation `'` (one quotation mark).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For instance, usually if entering the symbol `foo`, it returns the value of the corresponding variable (or an error, if there is no such variable).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] To refer to the literal symbol, enter `(quote foo)` or, usually, `'foo`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme also support the *backquote* operator (termed *quasiquote* in Scheme), entered with the ` character (Backtick).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is almost the same as the plain quote, except it allows expressions to be evaluated and their values interpolated into a quoted list with the comma `,` *unquote* and comma-at `,@` *splice* operators.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] If the variable `snue` has the value `(bar baz)` then `(foo ,snue) evaluates to `(foo (bar baz))`, while `(foo ,@snue) evaluates to `(foo bar baz)`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The backquote is most often used in defining macro expansions.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Self-evaluating forms and quoted forms are Lisp's equivalent of literals.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It may be possible to modify the values of (mutable) literals in program code.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if a function returns a quoted form, and the code that calls the function modifies the form, this may alter the behavior of the function on subsequent invocations.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Modifying a quoted form like this is generally considered bad style, and is defined by ANSI Common Lisp as erroneous (resulting in "undefined" behavior in compiled files, because the file-compiler can coalesce similar constants, put them in write-protected memory, etc.).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp's formalization of quotation has been noted by Douglas Hofstadter (in *Gödel, Escher, Bach*) and others as an example of the philosophical idea of self-reference.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp family splits over the use of dynamic or static (a.k.a. lexical) scope.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure, Common Lisp and Scheme make use of static scoping by default, while newLISP, Picolisp and the embedded languages in Emacs and AutoCAD use dynamic scoping.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Since version 24.1, Emacs uses both dynamic and lexical scoping.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A fundamental distinction between Lisp and other languages is that in Lisp, the textual representation of a program is simply a human-readable description of the same internal data structures (linked lists, symbols, number, characters, etc.) as would be used by the underlying Lisp system.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp uses this to implement a very powerful macro system.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Like other macro languages such as the one defined by the C preprocessor (the macro preprocessor for the C, Objective-C and C++ programming languages), a macro returns code that can then be compiled.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, unlike C preprocessor macros, the macros are Lisp functions and so can exploit the full power of Lisp.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Further, because Lisp code has the same structure as lists, macros can be built with any of the list-processing functions in the language.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In short, anything that Lisp can do to a data structure, Lisp macros can do to code.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In contrast, in most other languages, the parser's output is purely internal to the language implementation and cannot be manipulated by the programmer.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This feature makes it easy to develop *efficient* languages within languages.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, the Common Lisp Object System can be implemented cleanly as a language extension using macros.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This means that if an application needs a different inheritance mechanism, it can use a different object system.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is in stark contrast to most other languages; for example, Java does not support multiple inheritance and there is no reasonable way to add it.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In simplistic Lisp implementations, this list structure is directly interpreted to run the program; a function is literally a piece of list structure which is traversed by the interpreter in executing it.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, most substantial Lisp systems also include a compiler.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The compiler translates list structure into machine code or bytecode for execution.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This code can run as fast as code compiled in conventional languages such as C.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Macros expand before the compilation step, and thus offer some interesting options.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] If a program needs a precomputed table, then a macro might create the table at compile time, so the compiler need only output the table and need not call code to create the table at run time.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp implementations even have a mechanism, `eval-when`, that allows code to be present during compile time (when a macro would need it), but not present in the emitted module.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp languages are often used with an interactive command line, which may be combined with an integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The user types in expressions at the command line, or directs the IDE to transmit them to the Lisp system.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp *reads* the entered expressions, *evaluates* them, and *prints* the result.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the Lisp command line is called a *read–eval–print loop* (REPL).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The basic operation of the REPL is as follows.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is a simplistic description which omits many elements of a real Lisp, such as quoting and macros.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The `read` function accepts textual S-expressions as input, and parses them into an internal data structure.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if you type the text `(+ 1 2)` at the prompt, `read` translates this into a linked list with three elements: the symbol `+`, the number 1, and the number 2.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It so happens that this list is also a valid piece of Lisp code; that is, it can be evaluated.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is because the car of the list names a function—the addition operation.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A `foo` will be read as a single symbol.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] `123` will be read as the number one hundred and twenty-three.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The `eval` function evaluates the data, returning zero or more other Lisp data as a result.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Evaluation does not have to mean interpretation; some Lisp systems compile every expression to native machine code.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It is simple, however, to describe evaluation as interpretation: To evaluate a list whose car names a function, `eval` first evaluates each of the arguments given in its cdr, then applies the function to the arguments.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In this case, the function is addition, and applying it to the argument list `(1 2)` yields the answer `3`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The symbol `foo` evaluates to the value of the symbol foo.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Data like the string "123" evaluates to the same string.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The list `(quote (1 2 3))` evaluates to the list (1 2 3).
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It is the job of the `print` function to represent output to the user.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For a simple result such as `3` this is trivial.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] An expression which evaluated to a piece of list structure would require that `print` traverse the list and print it out as an S-expression.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] To implement a Lisp REPL, it is necessary only to implement these three functions and an infinite-loop function.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] (Naturally, the implementation of `eval` will be complex, since it must also implement all special operators like `if` or `lambda`.) This done, a basic REPL is one line of code: `(loop (print (eval (read))))`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp REPL typically also provides input editing, an input history, error handling and an interface to the debugger.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In Common Lisp, arguments are evaluated in applicative order ('leftmost innermost'), while in Scheme order of arguments is undefined, leaving room for optimization by a compiler.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp originally had very few control structures, but many more were added during the language's evolution.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Programmers in the Scheme dialect often express loops using tail recursion.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Scheme's commonality in academic computer science has led some students to believe that tail recursion is the only, or the most common, way to write iterations in Lisp, but this is incorrect.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] All oft-seen Lisp dialects have imperative-style iteration constructs, from Scheme's `do` loop to Common Lisp's complex `loop` expressions.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] By contrast, ANSI Common Lisp does not require the optimization commonly termed a tail call elimination.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp control structures are *special operators*, equivalent to other languages' syntactic keywords.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Expressions using these operators have the same surface appearance as function calls, but differ in that the arguments are not necessarily evaluated—or, in the case of an iteration expression, may be evaluated more than once.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In contrast to most other major programming languages, Lisp allows implementing control structures using the language.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Several control structures are implemented as Lisp macros, and can even be macro-expanded by the programmer who wants to know how they work.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme have operators for non-local control flow.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The differences in these operators are some of the deepest differences between the two dialects.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Scheme supports *re-entrant continuations* using the `call/cc` procedure, which allows a program to save (and later restore) a particular place in execution.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp does not support re-entrant continuations, but does support several ways of handling escape continuations.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Often, the same algorithm can be expressed in Lisp in either an imperative or a functional style.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As noted above, Scheme tends to favor the functional style, using tail recursion and continuations to express control flow.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, imperative style is still quite possible.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The style preferred by many Common Lisp programmers may seem more familiar to programmers used to structured languages such as C, while that preferred by Schemers more closely resembles pure-functional languages such as Haskell.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because of Lisp's early heritage in list processing, it has a wide array of higher-order functions relating to iteration over sequences.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In many cases where an explicit loop would be needed in other languages (like a `for` loop in C) in Lisp the same task can be accomplished with a higher-order function.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A good example is a function which in Scheme is called `map` and in Common Lisp is called `mapcar`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This applies the `+` function to each corresponding pair of list elements, yielding the result `(11 22 33 44 55)`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp syntax lends itself naturally to recursion.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Mathematical problems such as the enumeration of recursively defined sets are simple to express in this notation.
[src:fennel-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Genera, renamed Open Genera, by Symbolics; Medley, written in Interlisp, originally a family of graphical operating systems that ran on Xerox's later Star workstations; Mezzano; Interim; ChrysaLisp, by developers of Tao Systems' TAOS; and also the Guix System for GNU/Linux.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua originated in 1993 as a language for extending software applications to meet the increasing demand for customization at the time.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] It provided the basic facilities of most procedural programming languages, but more complicated or domain-specific features were not included; rather, it included mechanisms for extending the language, allowing programmers to implement such features.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] As Lua was intended to be a general embeddable extension language, the designers of Lua focused on improving its speed, portability, extensibility and ease-of-use in development.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua was created in 1993 by Roberto Ierusalimschy, Luiz Henrique de Figueiredo, and Waldemar Celes, members of the Computer Graphics Technology Group (Tecgraf) at the Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro, in Brazil.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] From 1977 until 1992, Brazil had a policy of strong trade barriers (called a market reserve) for computer hardware and software, believing that Brazil could and should produce its own hardware and software.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] In that climate, Tecgraf's clients could not afford, either politically or financially, to buy customized software from abroad; under the market reserve, clients would have to go through a complex bureaucratic process to prove their needs couldn't be met by Brazilian companies.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Those reasons led Tecgraf to implement the basic tools it needed from scratch.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua's predecessors were the data-description and configuration languages Simple Object Language (SOL) and Data-Entry Language (DEL).
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] They had been independently developed at Tecgraf in 1992–1993 to add some flexibility into two different projects (both were interactive graphical programs for engineering applications at Petrobras company).
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] There was a lack of any flow-control structures in SOL and DEL, and Petrobras felt a growing need to add full programming power to them.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua 1.0 was designed in such a way that its object constructors, being then slightly different from the current light and flexible style, incorporated the data-description syntax of SOL (hence the name Lua: *Sol* meaning "Sun" in Portuguese, and *Lua* meaning "Moon").
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Dobb's Journal*, Lua's creators also state that LISP and Scheme with their single, ubiquitous data-structure mechanism (the list) were a major influence on their decision to develop the table as the primary data structure of Lua.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua semantics have been increasingly influenced by Scheme over time, especially with the introduction of anonymous functions and full lexical scoping.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Several features were added in new Lua versions.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Versions of Lua prior to version 5.0 were released under a license similar to the BSD license.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] From version 5.0 onwards, Lua has been licensed under the MIT License.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Both are permissive free software licences and are almost identical.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua is commonly described as a "multi-paradigm" language, providing a small set of general features that can be extended to fit different problem types.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua does not contain explicit support for inheritance, but allows it to be implemented with metatables.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] In general, Lua strives to provide simple, flexible meta-features that can be extended as needed, rather than supply a feature-set specific to one programming paradigm.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] As a result, the base language is light; the full reference interpreter is only about 293 kB compiled and easily adaptable to a broad range of applications.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] As a dynamically typed language intended for use as an extension language or scripting language, Lua is compact enough to fit on a variety of host platforms.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] It supports only a small number of atomic data structures such as Boolean values, numbers (double-precision floating point and 64-bit integers by default) and strings.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Typical data structures such as arrays, sets, lists and records can be represented using Lua's single native data structure, the table, which is essentially a heterogeneous associative array.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua implements a small set of advanced features such as first-class functions, garbage collection, closures, proper tail calls, coercion (automatic conversion between string and number values at run time), coroutines (cooperative multitasking) and dynamic module loading.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The declaration of a variable, without a value.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] A comment in Lua starts with a double-hyphen and runs to the end of the line, similar to Ada, Eiffel, Haskell, SQL and VHDL.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Multi-line strings and comments are marked with double square brackets.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua has one type of conditional test: `if then end` with optional `else` and `elseif then` execution control constructs.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua has four types of conditional loops: the `while` loop, the `repeat` loop (similar to a `do while` loop), the numeric `for` loop and the generic `for` loop.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Loops can also be nested (put inside of another loop).
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Any future calls to `print` will now be routed through the new function, and because of Lua's lexical scoping, the old print function will only be accessible by the new, modified print.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] A new closure for the variable `x` is created every time `addto` is called, so that each new anonymous function returned will always access its own `x` parameter.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The closure is managed by Lua's garbage collector, just like any other object.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Tables are the most important data structures (and, by design, the only built-in composite data type) in Lua and are the foundation of all user-created types.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] They are associative arrays with addition of automatic numeric key and special syntax.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] A table is a set of key and data pairs, where the data is referenced by key; in other words, it is a hashed heterogeneous associative array.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Tables are created using the `{}` constructor syntax.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Tables are always passed by reference (see Call by sharing).
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] A key (index) can be any value except `nil` and NaN, including functions.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] A table is often used as structure (or record) by using strings as keys.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Because such use is very common, Lua features a special syntax for accessing such fields.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] By using a table to store related functions, it can act as a namespace.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Tables are automatically assigned a numerical key, enabling them to be used as an array data type.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The first automatic index is 1 rather than 0 as it is for many other programming languages (though an explicit index of 0 is allowed).
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] A numeric key `1` is distinct from a string key `"1"`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The length of a table `t` is defined to be any integer index `n` such that `t[n]` is not `nil` and `t[n+1]` is `nil`; moreover, if `t[1]` is `nil`, `n` can be zero.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] For a regular array, with non-nil values from 1 to a given `n`, its length is exactly that `n`, the index of its last value.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] If the array has "holes" (that is, nil values between other non-nil values), then `#t` can be any of the indices that directly precedes a `nil` value (that is, it may consider any such nil value as the end of the array).
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Using a hash map to emulate an array is normally slower than using an actual array; however, Lua tables are optimized for use as arrays to help avoid this issue.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Extensible semantics is a key feature of Lua, and the metatable allows powerful customization of tables.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The following example demonstrates an "infinite" table.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] For any `n`, `fibs[n]` will give the `n`-th Fibonacci number using dynamic programming and memoization.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Although Lua does not have a built-in concept of classes, object-oriented programming can be emulated using functions and tables.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] An object is formed by putting methods and fields in a table.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Inheritance (both single and multiple) can be implemented with metatables, delegating nonexistent methods and fields to a parent object.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] There is no such concept as "class" with these techniques; rather, prototypes are used, similar to Self or JavaScript.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] New objects are created either with a factory method (that constructs new objects from scratch) or by cloning an existing object.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Here, `setmetatable` tells Lua to look for an element in the `Vector` table if it is not present in the `vec` table.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] `vec.magnitude`, which is equivalent to `vec["magnitude"]`, first looks in the `vec` table for the `magnitude` element.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The `vec` table does not have a `magnitude` element, but its metatable delegates to the `Vector` table for the `magnitude` element when it's not found in the `vec` table.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua provides some syntactic sugar to facilitate object orientation.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] To declare member functions inside a prototype table, one can use `function table:func(args)`, which is equivalent to `function table.func(self, args)`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Calling class methods also makes use of the colon: `object:func(args)` is equivalent to `object.func(object, args)`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] It is possible to use metatables to mimic the behavior of class inheritance in Lua.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] In this example, we allow vectors to have their values multiplied by a constant in a derived class.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] It is also possible to implement multiple inheritance; `__index` can either be a function or a table.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Operator overloading can also be done; Lua metatables can have elements such as `__add`, `__sub` and so on.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua programs are not interpreted directly from the textual Lua file, but are compiled into bytecode, which is then run on the Lua virtual machine (VM).
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The compiling process is typically invisible to the user and is performed during run-time, especially when a just-in-time compilation (JIT) compiler is used, but it can be done offline to increase loading performance or reduce the memory footprint of the host environment by leaving out the compiler.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua bytecode can also be produced and executed from within Lua, using the `dump` function from the string library and the `load/loadstring/loadfile` functions.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua version 5.5.0 is implemented in approximately 32,000 lines of C code.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Like most CPUs, and unlike most virtual machines (which are stack-based), the Lua VM is register-based, and therefore more closely resembles most hardware design.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The register architecture both avoids excessive copying of values, and reduces the total number of instructions per function.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The virtual machine of Lua 5 is one of the first register-based pure VMs to have a wide use.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Parrot and Android's Dalvik are two other well-known register-based VMs.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua is intended to be embedded into other applications, and provides a C API for this purpose.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The API is divided into two parts: the Lua core and the Lua auxiliary library.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The Lua API's design eliminates the need for manual reference counting (management) in C code, unlike Python's API.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The API, like the language, is minimalist.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Advanced functions are provided by the auxiliary library, which consists largely of preprocessor macros which assist with complex table operations.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua provides functions to push and pop most simple C data types (integers, floats, etc.) to and from the stack, and functions to manipulate tables through the stack.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The Lua stack is somewhat different from a traditional stack; the stack can be indexed directly, for example.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Negative indices indicate offsets from the top of the stack.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] For example, −1 is the top (most recently pushed value), while positive indices indicate offsets from the bottom (oldest value).
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Marshalling data between C and Lua functions is also done using the stack.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] To call a Lua function, arguments are pushed onto the stack, and then the `lua_call` is used to call the actual function.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] When writing a C function to be directly called from Lua, the arguments are read from the stack.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] The C API also provides some special tables, located at various "pseudo-indices" in the Lua stack.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] At `LUA_GLOBALSINDEX` prior to Lua 5.2 is the globals table, `_G` from within Lua, which is the main namespace.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] There is also a registry located at `LUA_REGISTRYINDEX` where C programs can store Lua values for later retrieval.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Besides standard library (core) modules it is possible to write extensions using the Lua API.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Extension modules are shared objects which can be used to extend the functions of the interpreter by providing native facilities to Lua scripts.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Lua scripts may load extension modules using `require`, just like modules written in Lua itself, or with `package.loadlib`.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] When a C library is loaded via `require('foo')` Lua will look for the function `luaopen_foo` and call it, which acts as any C function callable from Lua and generally returns a table filled with methods.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] A growing set of modules termed *rocks* are available through a package management system named LuaRocks, in the spirit of CPAN, RubyGems and Python eggs.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Prewritten Lua bindings exist for most popular programming languages, including other scripting languages.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] For C++, there are a number of template-based approaches and some automatic binding generators.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] In video game development, Lua is widely used as a scripting language, mainly due to its perceived ease of embedding, fast execution, and short learning curve.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Notable games which use Lua include *Roblox*, *Garry's Mod*, *World of Warcraft*, *Payday 2*, *Project Zomboid*, *Phantasy Star Online 2*, *Dota 2*, *Crysis*, and many others.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] Also, Lua is used in non-video game software, such as Adobe Lightroom, Moho, iClone, Aerospike, and some system software in FreeBSD and NetBSD, and used as a template scripting language on MediaWiki using the Scribunto extension.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] In 2003, a poll conducted by GameDev.net showed that Lua was the most popular scripting language for game programming.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] On 12 January 2012, Lua was announced as a winner of the Front Line Award 2011 from the magazine *Game Developer* in the category Programming Tools.
[src:fennel-lisp/lua-programming-language] In addition, the Lua users community provides some *power patches* on top of the reference C implementation.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] In computer programming, a **macro** (short for "**macro instruction**"; from Greek μακρο*-* 'long, large') is a rule or pattern that specifies how a certain input should be mapped to a replacement output.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Applying a macro to an input is known as **macro expansion**.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The input and output may be a sequence of lexical tokens or characters, or a syntax tree.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Character macros are supported in software applications to make it easy to invoke common command sequences.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Token and tree macros are supported in some programming languages to enable code reuse or to extend the language, sometimes for domain-specific languages.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Macros are used to make a sequence of computing instructions available to the programmer as a single program statement, making the programming task less tedious and less error-prone.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Thus, they are called "macros" because a "big" block of code can be expanded from a "small" sequence of characters.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Macros often allow positional or keyword parameters that dictate what the conditional assembler program generates and have been used to create entire programs or program suites according to such variables as operating system, platform or other factors.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The term derives from "macro instruction", and such expansions were originally used in generating assembly language code.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] During the 1980s, macro programs – originally SmartKey, then SuperKey, KeyWorks, Prokey – were very popular, first as a means to automatically format screenplays, then for a variety of user-input tasks.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] These programs were based on the terminate-and-stay-resident mode of operation and applied to all keyboard input, no matter in which context it occurred.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] They have to some extent fallen into obsolescence following the advent of mouse-driven user interfaces and the availability of keyboard and mouse macros in applications, such as word processors and spreadsheets, making it possible to create application-sensitive keyboard macros.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Keyboard macros can be used in massively multiplayer online role-playing games (MMORPGs) to perform repetitive, but lucrative tasks, thus accumulating resources.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] As this is done without human effort, it can skew the economy of the game.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] For this reason, use of macros is a violation of the TOS or EULA of most MMORPGs, and their administrators spend considerable effort to suppress them.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Keyboard and mouse macros that are created using an application's built-in macro features are sometimes called **application macros**.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] They are created by carrying out the sequence once and letting the application record the actions.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] An underlying macro programming language, most commonly a scripting language, with direct access to the features of the application may also exist.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The programmers' text editor Emacs (short for "editing macros") follows this idea to a conclusion.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] In effect, most of the editor is made of macros.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Emacs was originally devised as a set of macros in the editing language TECO; it was later ported to dialects of Lisp.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Another programmers' text editor, Vim (a descendant of vi), also has an implementation of keyboard macros.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] It can record into a register (macro) what a person types on the keyboard and it can be replayed or edited just like VBA macros for Microsoft Office.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Vim also has a scripting language called Vimscript to create macros.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) is a programming language included in Microsoft Office from Office 97 through Office 2019 (although it was available in some components of Office prior to Office 97).
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] However, its function has evolved from and replaced the macro languages that were originally included in some of these applications.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] XEDIT, running on the Conversational Monitor System (CMS) component of VM, supports macros written in EXEC, EXEC2 and REXX, and some CMS commands were actually wrappers around XEDIT macros.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The Hessling Editor (THE), a partial clone of XEDIT, supports Rexx macros using Regina and Open Object REXX (oorexx).
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Many common applications, and some on PCs, use Rexx as a scripting language.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] VBA has access to most Microsoft Windows system calls and executes when documents are opened.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] This makes it relatively easy to write computer viruses in VBA, commonly known as macro viruses.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] In the mid-to-late 1990s, this became one of the most common types of computer virus.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] However, during the late 1990s and to date, Microsoft has been patching and updating its programs.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] In addition, current anti-virus programs immediately counteract such attacks.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] A **parameterized macro** is a macro that is able to insert given objects into its expansion.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] This gives the macro some of the power of a function.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] This causes `PI` to always be replaced with `3.14159` wherever it occurs.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] What this macro expands to depends on what argument *x* is passed to it.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Parameterized macros are a useful source-level mechanism for performing in-line expansion, but in languages such as C where they use simple textual substitution, they have a number of severe disadvantages over other mechanisms for performing in-line expansion, such as inline functions.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The parameterized macros used in languages such as Lisp, PL/I and Scheme, on the other hand, are much more powerful, able to make decisions about what code to produce based on their arguments; thus, they can effectively be used to perform run-time code generation.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Languages such as C and some assembly languages have rudimentary macro systems, implemented as preprocessors to the compiler or assembler.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] C preprocessor macros work by simple textual substitution at the token, rather than the character level.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] However, the macro facilities of more sophisticated assemblers, e.g., IBM High Level Assembler (HLASM) can't be implemented with a preprocessor; the code for assembling instructions and data is interspersed with the code for assembling macro invocations.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] A classic use of macros is in the computer typesetting system TeX and its derivatives, where most functionality is based on macros.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] MacroML is an experimental system that seeks to reconcile static typing and macro systems.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Nemerle has typed syntax macros, and one productive way to think of these syntax macros is as a multi-stage computation.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Some major applications have been written as text macro invoked by other applications, e.g., by XEDIT in CMS.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Some languages, such as PHP, can be embedded in free-format text, or the source code of other languages.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The mechanism by which the code fragments are recognised (for instance, being bracketed by `<?php` and `?>`) is similar to a textual macro language, but they are much more powerful, fully featured languages.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Macros in the PL/I language are written in a subset of PL/I itself: the compiler executes "preprocessor statements" at compilation time, and the output of this execution forms part of the code that is compiled.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The ability to use a familiar procedural language as the macro language gives power much greater than that of text substitution macros, at the expense of a larger and slower compiler.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Macros in PL/I, as well as in many assemblers, may have side effects, e.g., setting variables that other macros can access.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Frame technology's frame macros have their own command syntax but can also contain text in any language.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Each frame is both a generic component in a hierarchy of nested subassemblies, and a procedure for integrating itself with its subassembly frames (a recursive process that resolves integration conflicts in favor of higher level subassemblies).
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The outputs are custom documents, typically compilable source modules.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Frame technology can avoid the proliferation of similar but subtly different components, an issue that has plagued software development since the invention of macros and subroutines.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Most assembly languages have less powerful procedural macro facilities, for example allowing a block of code to be repeated N times for loop unrolling; but these have a completely different syntax from the actual assembly language.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Macro systems—such as the C preprocessor described earlier—that work at the level of lexical tokens cannot preserve the lexical structure reliably.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Syntactic macro systems work instead at the level of abstract syntax trees, and preserve the lexical structure of the original program.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The most widely used implementations of syntactic macro systems are found in Lisp-like languages.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] These languages are especially suited for this style of macro due to their uniform, parenthesized syntax (known as S-expressions).
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] In particular, uniform syntax makes it easier to determine the invocations of macros.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Lisp macros transform the program structure itself, with the full language available to express such transformations.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] While syntactic macros are often found in Lisp-like languages, they are also available in other languages such as Prolog, Erlang, Dylan, Scala, Nemerle, Rust, Elixir, Nim, Haxe, and Julia.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] They are also available as third-party extensions to JavaScript and C#.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Before Lisp had macros, it had so-called FEXPRs, function-like operators whose inputs were not the values computed by the arguments but rather the syntactic forms of the arguments, and whose output were values to be used in the computation.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] In other words, FEXPRs were implemented at the same level as EVAL, and provided a window into the meta-evaluation layer.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] This was generally found to be a difficult model to reason about effectively.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] In 1963, Timothy Hart proposed adding macros to Lisp 1.5 in AI Memo 57: MACRO Definitions for LISP.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] An anaphoric macro is a type of programming macro that deliberately captures some form supplied to the macro which may be referred to by an anaphor (an expression referring to another).
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Anaphoric macros first appeared in Paul Graham's On Lisp and their name is a reference to linguistic anaphora—the use of words as a substitute for preceding words.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Hygienic macros have been standardized for Scheme in the R5RS, R6RS, and R7RS standards.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] A number of competing implementations of hygienic macros exist such as `syntax-rules`, `syntax-case`, explicit renaming, and syntactic closures.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Both `syntax-rules` and `syntax-case` have been standardized in the Scheme standards.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Recently, Racket has combined the notions of hygienic macros with a "tower of evaluators", so that the syntactic expansion time of one macro system is the ordinary runtime of another block of code, and showed how to apply interleaved expansion and parsing in a non-parenthesized language.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] A number of languages other than Scheme either implement hygienic macros or implement partially hygienic systems.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Examples include Scala, Rust, Elixir, Julia, Dylan, Nim, and Nemerle.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] ) enables the creation of new syntactic constructs (e.g.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] ) indistinguishable from those built into the language.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] , it is possible to define the latter in terms of the former using macros.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] and hygienic macros, which enables a programmer to design their own control abstractions, such as looping and early exit constructs, without the need to build them into the language.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] can be implemented in a way that is both natural and efficient.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Macros can also be used to introduce new binding constructs.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] into the application of a function to a set of arguments.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Felleisen conjectures that these three categories make up the primary legitimate uses of macros in such a system.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Others have proposed alternative uses of macros, such as anaphoric macros in macro systems that are unhygienic or allow selective unhygienic transformation.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The interaction of macros and other language features has been a productive area of research.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] For example, components and modules are useful for large-scale programming, but the interaction of macros and these other constructs must be defined for their use together.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Module and component-systems that can interact with macros have been proposed for Scheme and other languages with macros.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] For example, the Racket language extends the notion of a macro system to a syntactic tower, where macros can be written in languages including macros, using hygiene to ensure that syntactic layers are distinct and allowing modules to export macros to other modules.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Macros are normally used to map a short string (macro invocation) to a longer sequence of instructions.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Another, less common, use of macros is to do the reverse: to map a sequence of instructions to a macro string.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] This was the approach taken by the STAGE2 Mobile Programming System, which used a rudimentary macro compiler (called SIMCMP) to map the specific instruction set of a given computer into *machine-independent* macros.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Applications (notably compilers) written in these machine-independent macros can then be run without change on any computer equipped with the rudimentary macro compiler.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The first application run in such a context is a more sophisticated and powerful macro compiler, written in the machine-independent macro language.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] This macro compiler is applied to itself, in a bootstrap fashion, to produce a compiled and much more efficient version of itself.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The advantage of this approach is that complex applications can be ported from one computer to a very different computer with very little effort (for each target machine architecture, just the writing of the rudimentary macro compiler).
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The advent of modern programming languages, notably C, for which compilers are available on virtually all computers, has rendered such an approach superfluous.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] This was, however, one of the first instances (if not the first) of compiler bootstrapping.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] A macro instruction embedded in the otherwise assembly source code would be processed by a macro compiler, a preprocessor to the assembler, to replace the macro with one or more assembly instructions.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The resulting code, pure assembly, would be translated to machine code by the assembler.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Two of the earliest programming installations to develop macro languages for the IBM 705 computer were at Dow Chemical Corp. in Delaware and the Air Material Command, Ballistics Missile Logistics Office in California.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Some consider macro instructions as an intermediate step between assembly language programming and the high-level programming languages that followed, such as FORTRAN and COBOL.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] By the late 1950s the macro language was followed by the Macro Assemblers.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] This was a combination of both where one program served both functions, that of a macro pre-processor and an assembler in the same package.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Early examples are FORTRAN Assembly Program (FAP) and Macro Assembly Program (IBMAP) on the IBM 709, 7094, 7040 and 7044, and Autocoder on the 7070/7072/7074.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Eastwood and Douglas McIlroy of Bell Labs introduced conditional and recursive macros into the popular SAP assembler, creating what is known as Macro SAP.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] McIlroy's 1960 paper was seminal in the area of extending any (including high-level) programming languages through macro processors.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Macro Assemblers allowed assembly language programmers to implement their own macro-language and allowed limited portability of code between two machines running the same CPU but different operating systems, for example, early versions of MS-DOS and CP/M-86.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] The macro library would need to be written for each target machine but not the overall assembly language program.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Note that more powerful macro assemblers allowed use of conditional assembly constructs in macro instructions that could generate different code on different machines or different operating systems, reducing the need for multiple libraries.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] In the 1980s and early 1990s, desktop PCs were only running at a few MHz and assembly language routines were commonly used to speed up programs written in C, Fortran, Pascal and others.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] These languages, at the time, used different calling conventions.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Macros could be used to interface routines written in assembly language to the front end of applications written in almost any language.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Again, the basic assembly language code remained the same, only the macro libraries needed to be written for each target language.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] In modern operating systems such as Unix and its derivatives, operating system access is provided through subroutines, usually provided by dynamic libraries.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] High-level languages such as C offer comprehensive access to operating system functions, obviating the need for assembler language programs for such functionality.
[src:fennel-lisp/macro-computer-science] Moreover, standard libraries of several newer programming languages, such as Go, actively discourage the use of syscalls in favor of platform-agnostic libraries as well if not necessary, to improve portability and security.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] In computer programming, an **S-expression** (or **symbolic expression**, abbreviated as **sexpr** or **sexp**) is an expression in a like-named notation for nested list (tree-structured) data.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] S-expressions were invented for, and popularized by, the programming language Lisp, which uses them for source code as well as data.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] *y*) where *x* and *y* are S-expressions.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] This definition reflects LISP's representation of a list as a series of "cells", each one an ordered pair.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] In plain lists, *y* points to the next cell (if any), thus forming a list.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] The recursive clause of the definition means that both this representation and the S-expression notation can represent any binary tree.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] `NIL` is the special end-of-list object (alternatively written `()`, which is the only representation in Scheme).
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] In the Lisp family of programming languages, S-expressions are used to represent both source code and data.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] Other uses of S-expressions are in Lisp-derived languages such as DSSSL, and as mark-up in communication protocols like IMAP and John McCarthy's CBCL.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] It is also used as text representation of WebAssembly.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] The details of the syntax and supported data types vary in the different languages, but the most common feature among these languages is the use of S-expressions and prefix notation.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] There are many variants of the S-expression format, supporting a variety of different syntaxes for different datatypes.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] The character `#` is often used to prefix extensions to the syntax, e.g.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] `#x10` for hexadecimal integers, or `#\C` for characters.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] When representing source code in Lisp, the first element of an S-expression is commonly an operator or function name and any remaining elements are treated as arguments.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] This is called "prefix notation" or "Polish notation".
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] As an example, the Boolean expression written `4 == (2 + 2)` in C, is represented as `(= 4 (+ 2 2))` in Lisp's s-expr-based prefix notation.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] As noted above, the precise definition of "atom" varies across LISP-like languages.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] A quoted string can typically contain anything but a quote, while an unquoted identifier atom can typically contain anything but quotes, whitespace characters, parentheses, brackets, braces, backslashes, and semicolons.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] In either case, a prohibited character can typically be included by escaping it with a preceding backslash.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] The recursive case of the definition of S-expressions is traditionally implemented using cons cells.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] S-expressions were originally intended only for data to be manipulated by M-expressions, but the first implementation of Lisp was an interpreter of S-expression encodings of M-expressions, and Lisp programmers soon became accustomed to using S-expressions for both code and data.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] This means that Lisp is homoiconic; that is, the primary representation of programs is also a data structure in a primitive type of the language itself.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] Nested lists can be written as S-expressions: `((milk juice) (honey marmalade))` is a two-element S-expression whose elements are also two-element S-expressions.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] The whitespace-separated notation used in Lisp (and this article) is typical.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] Line breaks (newline characters) usually qualify as separators.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] Program code can be written in S-expressions, usually using prefix notation.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] S-expressions can be read in Lisp using the function READ.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] READ reads the textual representation of an S-expression and returns Lisp data.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] The function PRINT can be used to output an S-expression.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] The output then can be read with the function READ, when all printed data objects have a readable representation.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] Lisp has readable representations for numbers, strings, symbols, lists and many other data types.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] Program code can be formatted as pretty printed S-expressions using the function PPRINT (note: with two Ps, short for *pretty*-print).
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] Lisp programs are valid S-expressions, but not all S-expressions are valid Lisp programs.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] `(1.0 + 3.1)` is a valid S-expression, but not a valid Lisp program, since Lisp uses prefix notation and a floating point number (here 1.0) is not valid as an operation (the first element of the expression).
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] An S-expression preceded by a single quotation mark, as in `'x`, is syntactic sugar for a quoted S-expression, in this case `(quote x)`.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] S-expressions are also used for WebAssembly text format.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] S-expressions are often compared to XML: one key difference is that S-expressions have just one form of containment, the dotted pair, while XML tags can contain simple attributes, other tags, or CDATA, each using different syntax.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] Another is that S-expressions do not define a reference mechanism, whereas XML provides a notion of unique identifiers and references to them.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] For simple use cases, S-expressions are simpler than XML, but for more advanced use cases, XML has a query language called XPath which many tools and third party libraries use to simplify the handling of XML data.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] Standards for some Lisp-derived programming languages include a specification for their S-expression syntax.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] These include Common Lisp (ANSI standard document ANSI INCITS 226-1994 (R2004)), Scheme (R5RS and R6RS), and ISLISP.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] In May 1997, Ron Rivest submitted an Internet Draft to be considered for publication as an RFC.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] The draft defined a syntax based on Lisp S-expressions but intended for general-purpose data storage and exchange (similar to XML) rather than specifically for programming.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] It was never approved as an RFC, but it has since been cited and used by other RFCs (e.g.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] RFC 2693) and several other publications.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] It was originally intended for use in SPKI.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] Rivest's format defines an S-expression as being either an octet-string (a series of bytes) or a finite list of other S-expressions.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] It describes three interchange formats for expressing this structure.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] One is the "advanced transport", which is very flexible in terms of formatting, and is syntactically similar to Lisp-style expressions, but they are not identical.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] The advanced transport, for example, allows octet-strings to be represented verbatim (the string's length followed by a colon and the entire raw string), a quoted form allowing escape characters, hexadecimal, Base64, or placed directly as a "token" if it meets certain conditions.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] Rivest's draft defines a canonical representation "for digital signature purposes".
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] It is intended to be compact, easier to parse, and unique for any abstract S-expression.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] It only allows verbatim strings, and prohibits whitespace as formatting outside strings.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] This format has not been widely adapted for use outside of SPKI (some of the users being GnuPG, libgcrypt, Nettle, and GNU lsh).
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] Rivest's S-expressions web page provides C source code for a parser and generator (available under the MIT license), which could be adapted and embedded into other programs.
[src:fennel-lisp/s-expression] In addition, there are no restrictions on independently implementing the format.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] A source-to-source translator converts between programming languages that operate at approximately the same level of abstraction, while a traditional compiler translates from a higher level language to a lower level language.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] For example, a source-to-source translator may perform a translation of a program from Python to JavaScript, while a traditional compiler translates from a language like C to assembly or Java to bytecode.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] An automatic parallelizing compiler will frequently take in a high level language program as an input and then transform the code and annotate it with parallel code annotations (e.g., OpenMP) or language constructs (e.g.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Another purpose of source-to-source-compiling is translating legacy code to use the next version of the underlying programming language or an application programming interface (API) that breaks backward compatibility.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Transcompilers may either keep translated code structure as close to the source code as possible to ease development and debugging of the original source code or may change the structure of the original code so much that the translated code does not look like the source code.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Examples include Closure Compiler, CoffeeScript, Dart, Haxe, Opal, TypeScript and Emscripten.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] So called *Assembly language translators* are a class of source-to-source translators converting code from one assembly language into another, including (but not limited to) across different processor families and system platforms.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Intel marketed their 16-bit processor 8086 to be source compatible to the 8080, an 8-bit processor.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] To support this, Intel had an ISIS-II-based translator from 8080 to 8086 source code named CONV86 (also referred to as CONV-86 and CONVERT 86) available to OEM customers since 1978, possibly the earliest program of this kind.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] It supported multiple levels of translation and ran at 2 MHz on an Intel Microprocessor Development System MDS-800 with 8-inch floppy drives.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] According to user reports, it did not work very reliably.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Seattle Computer Products (SCP) offered TRANS86.COM, written by Tim Paterson in 1980 while developing 86-DOS.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Also, performing only a mere transliteration, the brute-force single-pass translator did not carry out any register and jump optimizations.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] The SCP version 1 of TRANS86.COM ran on Z80-based systems.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Once 86-DOS was running, Paterson, in a self-hosting-inspired approach, utilized TRANS86 to convert itself into a program running under 86-DOS.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Numbered version 2, this was named TRANS.COM instead.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Later in 1982, the translator was apparently also available from Microsoft.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Also named TRANS86, Sorcim offered an 8080 to 8086 translator as well since December 1980.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Like SCP's program it was designed to port CP/M-80 application code (in ASM, MAC, RMAC or ACT80 assembly format) to MS-DOS (in a format compatible with ACT86).
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] In ACT80 format it also supported a few Z80 mnemonics.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] The translation occurred on an instruction-by-instruction basis with some optimization applied to conditional jumps.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] The program ran under CP/M-80, MP/M-80 and Cromemco DOS with a minimum of 24 KB of RAM, and had no restrictions on the source file size.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Much more sophisticated and the first to introduce optimizing compiler technologies into the source translation process was Digital Research's XLT86 1.0 in September 1981.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] The program was written by Gary Kildall and translated .ASM source code for the Intel 8080 processor (in a format compatible with ASM, MAC or RMAC assemblers) into .A86 source code for the 8086 (compatible with ASM86).
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] XLT86.COM itself was written in PL/I-80 for CP/M-80 platforms.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] The program occupied 30 KB of RAM for itself plus additional memory for the program graph.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] On a 64 KB memory system, the maximum source file size supported was about 6 KB, so that larger files had to be broken down accordingly before translation.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Alternatively, XLT86 was also available for DEC VAX/VMS.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Although XLT86's input and output worked on source-code level, the translator's in-memory representation of the program and the applied code optimizing technologies set the foundation to binary recompilation.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] 2500 AD Software offered an 8080 to 8086 source-code translator as part of their XASM suite for CP/M-80 machines with Z80 as well as for Zilog ZEUS and Olivetti PCOS systems.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Since 1979, Zilog offered a Z80 to Z8000 translator as part of their PDS 8000 development system.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Advanced Micro Computers (AMC) and 2500 AD Software offered Z80 to Z8000 translators as well.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] The latter was named TRANS and was available for Z80 CP/M, CP/M-86, MS-DOS and PCOS.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] The Z88DK development kit provides a Z80 to i486 source code translator targeting nasm named "to86.awk", written in 2008 by Stefano Bodrato.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] It is in turn based on an 8080 to Z80 converter written in 2003 by Douglas Beattie, Jr., named "toz80.awk".
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] In 2021, Brian Callahan wrote an 8080 CP/M 2.2 to MS-DOS source code translator targeting nasm named 8088ify.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] The first implementations of some programming languages started as transcompilers, and the default implementation for some of those languages are still transcompilers.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] In addition to the table below, a CoffeeScript maintainer provides a list of languages that compile to JavaScript.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] When developers want to switch to a different language while retaining most of an existing codebase, it might be better to use a transcompiler compared to rewriting the whole software by hand.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Depending on the quality of the transcompiler, the code may or may not need manual intervention in order to work properly.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] This is different from "transcompiled languages" where the specifications demand that the output source code always works without modification.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] All transcompilers used to port a codebase will expect manual adjustment of the output source code if there is a need to achieve maximum code quality in terms of readability and platform convention.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] A transcompiler pipeline is what results from *recursive transcompiling*.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] By stringing together multiple layers of tech, with a transcompile step between each layer, technology can be repeatedly transformed, effectively creating a distributed language independent specification.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] XSLT is a general-purpose transform tool that can be used between many different technologies, to create such a derivative code pipeline.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] By repeating this process, one can turn A → B → C → D → E → F and then back into A(v2).
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] Some information will be preserved through this pipeline, from A → A(v2), and that information (at an abstract level) demonstrates what each of the components A–F agree on.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] In each of the different versions that the transcompiler pipeline produces, that information is preserved.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] It might take on many different shapes and sizes, but by the time it comes back to A (v2), having been transcompiled six times in the pipeline above, the information returns to its original state.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] This information which survives the transform through each format, from A–F–A(v2), is (by definition) derivative content or derivative code.
[src:fennel-lisp/transpiler] There are also debugging utilities that map the transcompiled source code back to the original code; for example, JavaScript source maps allow mapping of the JavaScript code executed by a web browser back to the original source in a transcompiled-to-JavaScript language.
